<m0>      When it comes to saving water, it's often the little things that count.<ep>
   Here are some water-saving tips to observe during Conserve Water/Detect-A-Leak-Week today through Saturday (May 5-11) and all year long.<ep>
   (box) Turn the water off while you brush your teeth; you'll save 3 gallons per brush.<ep>
   (box) Running only full loads in the washing machine and dishwasher can save 75 to 200 gallons per week.<ep>
   (box) It takes 30 to 40 gallons of water to fill a bathtub and 5 to 10 gallons of water per minute to take a shower. That means a shower will save water if you don't hog the hose.<ep>
   (box) Installing a flow restrictor in the shower will cut water use by as much as two-thirds.<ep>
   (box) Covering your swimming pool when it's not in use will prevent evaporation of as much as 1,300 gallons.<ep>
   (box) If you keep a bottle of water in the refrigerator for drinking, you don't have to run the tap until the water gets cold enough to drink. This saves 200 to 300 gallons per week.<ep>
   (box) To reduce water flow in toilets, install a plastic water bottle weighted down with pebbles in the tank, or switch to a low-flow toilet that cuts the amount of water used per flush from 5 to 10 gallons to 1.6 gallons or less. Don't be fooled by the old handyman's solution of installing a brick in the toilet tank; a brick can dissolve slightly, causing clogging problems.<ql>
